He brought out  the freshly baked flatbread which was so good along with the three accompanying sauces which added delightful flavors.  We all tried different entrees which were all delicious, lamb, beef, ravioli and a vegetarian dish.  The atmosphere was very nice and they seated the six of us at a round table which  made conversation easy among all.  Overall it was a wonderful meal and would highly recommend.  We will come back if ever in Boston again.  Thank you Helmand Restaurant and Wais for a lovely meal our last night in Boston.  Wishing you continued success with your restaurant.

SUMMARY: It’s the first Afghan restaurant I’ve been to. It’s a beautifully decorated, authentic feeling restaurant. Appetizers and soups were flavorful and unique, though I was surprised at the similarities between Indian and Afghani cuisine on my entrée. Great service.  ITEMS ORDERED: Kaddo (baked baby pumpkin appetizer topped with yogurt garlic sauce and ground beef sauce); Mushawa (lamb and yogurt soup); Lam Lawand.  PROs: It’s a dimly-lit, beautifully decorated restaurant that appears authentic in design with some museum-like displays. The appetizer and soup were all flavorful and unique. The staff is warm and friendly, and an older crowd make up most of the patrons. The staff was friendly, and my server was very helpful and courteous.  CONs/CONSIDERATIONS: The entrée bore striking resemblance to Indian food for me. I’m unsure if that’s the norm, though I suppose it’s not surprising given the proximity between the two countries. Also, the lamb in my entrée was quite dry, and didn’t have too much flavor except from the sauce that accompanied it. I found it disappointing. This is a big deal for me since (1) the entrée is the foundation for a meal, and (2) the entrée was a recommendation by the server as one of the more popular items.  RATING: I’m tempted to assign a 3-star rating to Helmand because of my disappointment in the entrée. However, because I felt Helmand exceled in all other areas (appetizer, service, environment and décor), I’m opting to provide 4 stars. I’ll be back to try other entrées in the future.

There’s also a very diverse wine selection. I got to taste the aushak appetizer, the lamb lawand entree, and the seekh kabab entree (spelling?), and everything was excellent. I suggest ordering an entree with lamb, it’s expertly prepared. Also, don’t skip dessert! The backlawa was divine, and the rice pudding was decadent. The atmosphere in the restaurant is warm and inviting, and the waitstaff are incredibly attentive and helpful. I can’t wait to come again!

Definitely worth a try. The bread is baked in front of you in a wood-fired oven. It is the #1 attraction. The food is flavorful, although you can't help thinking it's a little too Americanized: the stewed meats are so lean that they are sadly dry, the Kaddo (a must try squash appetizer) is a little too sweet. Still, overall you will leave with a full stomach and a happy feeling.
Really good food. If you like Mediterranean or middle-eastern, this is a great place. And if you've never had it, you need to try this.
I like this place Lamb Chops
Fast service, delicious food,  reasonable prices.

Absolutely delicious! Never tried afgan food before but every single thing we ordered tasted amazing. We were served different sauces to start with a basket of flat, freshly made bread. We got to sit right by their big stone oven so we saw it coming out fresh. Then we got an appetizer that was two thin-crust pockets: one filled with sauteed leeks, the other filled with spiced potatoes. They were served with a very think yogurt. These were seriously so good!! For our entree, one of us had the special vegetarian, which had okra, pumpkin, eggplant, and spinach served with rice. I had a nightly special of mung beans and black eyed peas, kind of like a gumbo but the flavor was so amazing; served with a poblano pepper baked and stuffed with sauteed spinach, and covered in cheese. Omg can't even describe how good everything tasted! Only con is that the dishes are a little pricey (average $16-22/plate, lowest seemed to be $14 highest seemed to be $28), and their wine list wasn't the best (lots of new world wines and pricey). Place has a full bar and the staff was so sweet and friendly. They have you check backpacks with the hostess, but it wasn't a big deal, they were very professionally about it. This place is so delicious, try something new, GO EAT HERE! :)
This was our first time eating that kind of food, but I have to say it was out of this world! The service and staff was great! Definitely recommend!
Beautiful interior, friendly staff, wonderful food
Good food, good ambience, cordial staff made it a good experience
First time and we will definitely come back!

***Not representative of Afgani food or hospitality.***  We had made called and reserved a table in advance, and asked for a window table. Instead, the server put us in the very back of the restaurant. The server was quite nice, but the service was really slow and food was - Cold, and Terrible, and Overpriced !!!.  Our server was struggling to attend to all the tables, and we wasted a lot of time waiting for him. We saw him make coffee out in the middle of tables (that took a while !). There are a lot of tables in this place, and it feels more of an assembly line operation than authentic Afgani.  Not recommended at all !

I have had mixed experiences here for lunch and dinner over the past 15 years. Helmand has the distinction of being the first Afghan restaurant in the Boston area, but it takes itself a little too seriously and is a little overpriced. Easy walk from the MBTA green line train Lechmere station. Paid garage parking across the street.

You know when you are near it because you can smell it a half mile away.  The bread is handmade and the sauces only make it better.  The steak can be cut with your fork it a so tender. I loved this place 10 years ago, but was disappointed visiting it recently. The food seems like it has been Americanised since my last visit -- dishes were either much milder flavorwise or sweeter than I recalled. Perhaps I am just being nostalgic and don't remember it correctly, but it seems like they are playing it safe.  Having said that, this is still a good restaurant serving dishes you are unlikely to find elsewhere.

Incredibly authentic and tasty place for Afghan food. Try the lamb dishes, especially the Qabelee. The soft-stewed lamb and spicy moist rice is just unique and heavenly.

I take people visiting me in Boston to this place all the time or if I want to treat someone to one of the most authentic Middle Eastern meals i've ever had outside the Middle East. Their Mantwo, Aushok and Qabeeli are to die for, although I do prefer my Qabeeli without the raisins!

Very cozy, warm decor, and friendly service.   Love the fact they have a full bar now!     This is a fine, romantic place to explore Afghan cuisine.  As others have said, the 'kaddo' pumpkin dish prepared vegetarian style without the ground meat, is just fantastic. The trout with walnuts and dates that we had last night was outstanding.

This is the second time I came here. The first time I came I wanted to give 10 stars out of 5. It was so good. However, this time I was severely disappointed. The waiter asked if we wanted wine and when we said no, she looked so dissappointed and angry that we were surprised. We hadn't asked her any information about it either to make her feel we wanted wine. Then, someone else served us food which went well. The food didn't taste that great. Don't get me wrong, it was good, just not perfect like last time. Then we ordered dessert and some coffee, both were very good, and hence I have given 3 stars. I got left overs packed and they charged me for a brown bag. I know stores charge for plastic bags but what kind of a cheap restaurant charges for a brown bag? Moreover, in their suggested tip section, they added the tip on the total amount including tax instead of just food. Most restaurants write the suggested tip based on just food. The guy who came to give us the check talked to us very politely and explained our waiter was busy and hence, he was collecting the check. He thanked us for coming as well. I think we just got unlucky with waiter who served us.
